    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1948-06-27T04:00:00-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1948-06-27T04:00:00-05:00" n="481"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d481">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">840.50 Recovery/6–2748: Telegram</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Ambassador in China</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Stuart</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                            State</gloss>
                    </hi>
                </head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">
                        <placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Nanking</hi>
                        </placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1948-06-27T18:00:00+09:00"
                            >June 27, 1948—6 p.m.</date>
                        <lb/>[Received June 27—8:21 a.m.]</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>1167. At this moment of financial crisis and disquietude symptomized by student
                    attacks on me personally, I feel impelled to point out in connection with
                    negotiation of bilateral aid agreement that our larger interests may well be
                    most effectively served by dealing generously with the Chinese and avoiding
                    imposition of terms of/or language which will lose face for present Cabinet and
                    hence expose it to intensified criticism. There are certain hopeful signs in the
                    general situation, dark though it appears on certain fronts.</p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>
                        <hi rend="smallcaps">Stuart</hi>
                    </signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
